hints_latex:
Recall the definition of the cumulative distribution function \emph{F}
of a continuous random variable with probability density function
\emph{p}:

\begin{align*}
F(\theta) = \int_{-\infty}^\theta p(t)\,dt
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
Solving first for the cdf in terms of $\displaystyle \theta$, using that
\emph{p(t) = 0} for \emph{t \textless{} -$\pi$/4}, we have

\begin{align*}
F(\theta) &= \int_{-\pi/4}^{\theta}\frac{2}{\pi}\,dt = \left.\frac{2}{\pi}t \right|_{-\pi/4}^{\theta} \\
&= \frac{2}{\pi}\left(\theta - \frac{-\pi}4\right)
\end{align*}

To find the cdf in terms of \emph{x} we note that, from the diagram,
$\displaystyle \tan(\theta) = \tfrac{x}{2}$. Solving for \emph{$\theta$} gives
$\displaystyle \theta = \arctan(\tfrac{x}{2})$ and thus we have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle F(x) = \frac2{\pi}\left(\arctan\left(\frac{x}{2}\right) + \frac{\pi}{4}\right)
\end{align*}

completing the problem.
